    = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Hu Ge''' ({{zh|c=\u80e1\u6b4c}}, born 20 September 1982), also known as '''Hugh Hu''', is a Chinese actor and singer. While studying at the [[Shanghai Theater Academy]], he was invited to play the leading role [[List of The Legend of Sword and Fairy characters|Li Xiaoyao]] in the 2005 television series ''[[Chinese Paladin (TV series)|Chinese Paladin]]'', and immediately skyrocketed to fame as one of China's most popular actors. Since then, he has starred in several iconic historical television series; such as ''[[The Little Fairy]]'' (2006), ''[[The Young Warriors (TV series)|The Young Warriors]]'' (2006), ''[[The Legend of the Condor Heroes (2008 TV series)|The Legend of the Condor Heroes]]'' (2008), ''[[Chinese Paladin 3 (TV series)|Chinese Paladin 3]]'' (2009), ''[[The Myth (TV series)|The Myth]]'' (2010), ''[[Xuan-Yuan Sword: Scar of Sky]]'' (2012) and ''[[Sound of the Desert (TV series)|Sound of the Desert]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite book |language=en, zh|author= |script-chapter=zh:\u300a\u80e1\u6b4c\uff0c\u597d\u4e45\u4e0d\u89c1\u300b|chapter=Long Time No See, Hu Ge|script-title=zh:\u300a\u82f1\u8bed\u8857\u300b|trans-title=Teen's Space |year=2018 |publisher=Chongqing Publishing House |location=Chongqing |pages=7\u20139 |isbn=978-7-229-13098-5}}</ref> \nIn September 2012, he was nominated for Best Newcomer at the 31st [[Baihua awards|Hundred Flowers Awards]] for his role as [[Lin Juemin]] in Chinese historical film [[1911 (film)|''1911'']] (2012). \nHu gained widespread acclaim with his roles as Ming Tai in the spy drama ''[[The Disguiser]]'' (2015) and [[List of Nirvana in Fire characters|Mei Changsu]] in the wuxia drama  ''[[Nirvana in Fire]]'', for which he received the Best Actor Award at the 22nd [[Shanghai Television Festival|Magnolia Awards]] and the [[China TV Golden Eagle Award|Golden Eagle Awards]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHu Ge was born in Shanghai on 20 September 1982. He received his first training in performing arts in Little Stars Performing Arts School run by Shanghai Media Group ([[Shanghai Media Group|SMG]]). Hu Ge attended Shanghai Xiang Yang Elementary School (1989\u201394) and [[Shanghai No.2 High School]] (1994\u20132001), both known for their educational rigor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/overseas/2016-04/11/c_128881634.htm|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u62db\u8001\u5e08\u559c\u6b22\uff1a\u60c5\u5546\u9ad8\u5b66\u4e60\u597d \u5f80\u64cd\u573a\u4e00\u5750\u5c31\u662f\u98ce\u666f|date=11 April 2016|agency=Xinhua News Agency|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.163.com/08/1208/17/4SLKNB8E00033310.html|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\uff1a\u62ff\u7740\u90ed\u5bcc\u57ce\u7684\u7167\u7247\u53bb\u526a\u4e09\u4e03\u5206\u53d1\u578b|date=8 December 2008|website=Netease|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to excellent academic work, Hu Ge's talents in a variety of extracurricular endeavors were also recognized. At age 14, Hu Ge started to host a popular TV show ''Sunshine Youth'' on Shanghai TV Education Channel for three years. Meanwhile, he was also selected to host a program in East Radio Shanghai. Hu Ge began his acting career by appearing in TV commercials, which helped him gain financial independence before graduating from high school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lady.people.com.cn/n/2015/1104/c1014-27776641.html|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c14\u5c81\u4e3b\u6301\u300a\u9633\u5149\u5c11\u5e74\u300b\u89c6\u9891\u66dd\u5149 \u970d\u5efa\u534e\u5468\u6770\u4f26\u9ec4\u6653\u660e \u53f2\u4e0a\u6700\u5168\u7537\u661f\u7ae5\u5e74\u7167|date=14 November 2015|website=People's Daily|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Hu Ge was admitted to two prestigious art institutes in China: the [[Central Academy of Drama]] and [[Shanghai Theatre Academy]]. Hu Ge decided to attend the latter, particularly attracted by its strong major in acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.163.com/11/1109/14/7IE6886Q00032DGD_all.html|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u665210\u5e74\u524d\u8003\u592e\u620f\u6210\u7ee9\u5355 \u7f51\u53cb\u9f50\u547c\u6b63\u592a\u7167\u5ae9\uff08\u5168\u6587\uff09|date=9 November 2011|website=Netease|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jx.people.com.cn/n/2015/1124/c190301-27167974-2.html|script-title=zh:\u63ed\u300a\u7405\u740a\u699c\u300b\u80e1\u6b4c\u4e0d\u4e3a\u4eba\u77e5\u7684\u827a\u8003\u751f\u6daf|date=24 November 2015|website=People's Daily|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2002\u20132006: Beginnings and Rise to fame===\nWhile he was still studying, Hu Ge was recommended by his friend to Chinese Entertainment Shanghai (now known as [[Tangren Media]]) where he acted as a voice dub actor for the 2002 drama ''The Book and the Sword''. Following which, he signed on with the company. After appearing in numerous commercials, Hu starred in the film ''Pretend There's No Feeling'' with a minor role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2005-01-04/12334712097s.shtml|script-title=zh:2005\u5185\u5730\u5a31\u4e50\u5708 80\u7248\u521d\u9732\u950b\u8292|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=4 January 2005|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref> His first television role was in the romance drama ''Dandelion''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.163.com/ent_2003/editor/news/starnews/040719/040719_264451.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u84b2\u516c\u82f1\u300b\u80e1\u6b4c:\u516d\u5c81\u5973\u5b69\u7684\"\u7238\u7238\"\u4e0d\u597d\u5f53|date=9 July 2004|website=Netease|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nHu rose to prominence in 2005 when he played [[List of The Legend of Sword and Fairy characters|Li Xiaoyao]] in ''[[Chinese Paladin (TV series)|Chinese Paladin]]'', a TV adaptation of the action RPG ''[[The Legend of Sword and Fairy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2005-07-07/1114773007.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u4ed9\u5251\u5947\u4fa0\u4f20\u300b\u6539\u7f16\u4e4b\u540c\u540d\u7535\u89c6\u5267\u5e26\u6765\u6536\u89c6\u72c2\u6f6e|date=7 July 2005|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> The television series was a major hit in China and launched Hu to instant fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://auto.sina.com.cn/news/2005-07-14/1655128183.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c \u900d\u9065\u6e38\u620f\u4e00\u591c\u6210\u540d(\u7ec4\u56fe)|date=14 July 2005|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> The theme song sung by him, \"June Rain\" was also widely popular.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/x/2005-03-25/0847685472.html|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\"\u516d\u6708\u7684\u96e8\"\u968f\u5267\u8d70\u7ea2|date=25 March 2006|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> The same year, he also portrayed Ning Caichen in the television series ''Strange Tales of Liao Zhai''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2007-07-06/16341627882.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u8042\u5c0f\u5029\u300b\u4e2d\u7ed3\u60c5\u8c0a \u6768\u5e42\u795d\u798f\u80e1\u6b4c\u590d\u51fa(\u56fe)|date=6 July 2007|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Chinese Paladin'', Hu Ge embarked on a number of other TV projects, most of which had a ''historical'' theme, most notably as Dong Yong in ''[[The Little Fairy]]'' (2006); based on the Chinese folktale ''[[Tian Xian Pei]]'' and as Yang Yanzhao in the ''[[The Young Warriors (TV series)|The Young Warriors]]'' (2006); based on the play ''[[The Generals of the Yang Family]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.qq.com/a/20060209/000139.htm|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u4e3b\u6f14\u53e4\u88c5\u5076\u50cf\u5267\u300a\u5929\u5916\u98de\u4ed9\u300b\u7684\u7231\u60c5\u6545\u4e8b|date=9 February 2006|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/x/2006-10-11/10511279225.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u5c11\u5e74\u6768\u5bb6\u5c06\u300b\u5f81\u6218\u8367\u5c4f|publisher=Sina Corp|date=11 October 2006|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref> He then starred in the horror film ''[[The 601st Phone Call]]'' (2006), where he received rave reviews for his performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2006-07-04/15141145846.html|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u6f14\u6280\u53d7\u5230\u597d\u8bc4 \u300a\u7b2c601\u4e2a\u7535\u8bdd\u300b\u4e2d\u8868\u73b0\u51fa\u8272|date=4 July 2006|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, Hu made his debut as a singer with the release of his first EP, titled ''Treasure''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.163.com/06/1026/11/2UBU675K00031NIL.html|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u53d1\u9996\u5f20\u4e13\u8f91 \u8bb0\u8005\u4f1a\u7535\u8bdd\u8fde\u7ebf|website=[[NetEase]]|date=26 October 2006|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132012: Comeback after accident and Continued success===\nAfter a hiatus, Hu returned to the screen and starred as [[Guo Jing]] in ''[[The Legend of the Condor Heroes (2008 TV series)|The Legend of the Condor Heroes]]'' (2008), adapted from [[Jin Yong|Louis Cha]]'s [[The Legend of the Condor Heroes|novel of the same title]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.qq.com/a/20090123/000113.htm|script-title=zh:\u65b0\u300a\u5c04\u96d5\u300b\u767b\u9646\u91cd\u5e86 \u6797\u4f9d\u6668\uff1a\u80e1\u6b4c\u6574\u5bb9\u540e\u66f4\u4eb2\u6c11|date=23 November 2009|website=Tencent|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> He also co-starred with [[Wu Chun]] and [[Charlene Choi]] in ''[[The Butterfly Lovers (2008 film)|The Butterfly Lovers]]'' (2008), based on the famous Chinese legend [[Butterfly Lovers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.news.cn/2008-08/18/content_9466835.htm|script-title=zh:\u4f24\u540e\u590d\u51fa\u9996\u6f14\"\u53cd\u6d3e\" \u300a\u5251\u8776\u300b\u672a\u6620\u80e1\u6b4c\u5148\"\u5fe7\"|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=18 August 2008|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 May 2008, Hu released his second album,''Start'', and embarked on his first solo concert in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/y/2008-05-13/13572024332.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u91ca\u6000\u8f66\u7978\u518d\u51fa\u53d1 \u4e0a\u6d77\u53ec\u5f00\u300a\u51fa\u53d1\u300b\u9996\u5531\u4f1a|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=13 May 2008|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.qq.com/a/20080509/000351.htm|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u503e\u60c5\u6253\u90202008\u5e74\u9996\u5f20\u4e2a\u4eba\u4e13\u8f91\u300a\u51fa\u53d1\u300b|website=[[Tencent]]|date=9 May 2008|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nHu then reprised his role as Li Xiaoyao ''[[Chinese Paladin 3 (TV series)|Chinese Paladin 3]]'' (2009) while simultaneously acting as three other characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2008-10-22/09522215832.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u300a\u4ed9\u52513\u300b\u4e2d\u4e00\u4eba\u5206\u9970\u4e09\u89d2|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=22 October 2008|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref> The series achieved high ratings and was awarded the Ratings Contribution award at the Sichuan Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2009-12-03/18212797347.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u4ed9\u5251\u4e09\u300b\u83b7\u591a\u9879\u6536\u89c6\u5927\u5956 \u6c5f\u82cf\u536b\u89c6\u5c06\u72ec\u5bb6\u4e0a\u661f|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=3 December 2009|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe next starred as the male protagonist in ''[[The Myth (TV series)|The Myth]]'' (2010), based on the 2005 Hong Kong [[The Myth (film)|film of the same title]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2009-12-29/10122827855.shtml|script-title=zh:\u7535\u89c6\u5267\u300a\u795e\u8bdd\u300b\u5c06\u767b\u592e\u516b \u80e1\u6b4c\u8e0f\u4e0a\"\u7a7f\u8d8a\"\u795e\u65c5|date=9 December 2009|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> The drama acquired very high viewership ratings, and boosted Hu's popularity to a new high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.163.com/10/0128/20/5U53ML5400032KMI.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u795e\u8bdd\u300b\u4e3a\u592e\u89c6\u8d5a1\u4ebf \u80e1\u6b4c\u88ab\u66dd\u7247\u916c12\u4e07\u4e00\u96c6|website=[[NetEase]]|date=28 January 2010|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref> Hu won the Popularity award at the 1st China Student Television Festival, and Best Actor in the fantasy genre at the 2010 [[Huading Awards]].<ref name=china>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2010-10-21/18303121278.shtml|script-title=zh:\u9996\u5c4a\u5927\u5b66\u751f\u7535\u89c6\u8282\u95ed\u5e55 \u5b59\u7ea2\u96f7\u738b\u73de\u4e39\u6700\u53d7\u559c\u7231|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=21 October 2010|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref><ref name=myth>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2010-11-15/19383146922.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u795e\u8bdd\u300b\u6536\u83b7\u534e\u9f0e\u5956 \u4e3b\u6f14\u76f8\u7ea6\u300a\u795e\u8bdd2\u300b|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=15 November 2010|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nTo avoid being typecast, Hu subsequently stopped accepting any role in period dramas after he finished filming ''The Myth''. He took on leading roles in modern dramas; ''Bitter Coffee (2011)'', ''Modern People'' (2012) and ''Unbeatable'' (2012), as well as war drama ''Shangri-La'' (2012).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://chinatibet.people.com.cn/7037193.html|title=Actor Hu Ge struggles with self for role in \"Shangri-la\"|website=[[People's Daily]]|date=23 June 2010|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> He also starred in the 2011 historical film [[1911 (film)|''1911'']], playing [[Lin Juemin]], and was nominated as Best New Actor at the 31st [[Hundred Flowers Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2011-09-22/15473424680.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u8f9b\u4ea5\u9769\u547d\u300b\u5c06\u6620 \u6797\u89c9\u6c11\u626e\u6f14\u8005\u80e1\u6b4c\u89e3\u8bfb\u89d2\u8272|date=22 September 2011|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=juemin>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinesefilms.cn/141/2012/08/22/141s11511.htm|title=Nomination List of the 31st China Hundred Flowers Awards Unveiled|website=Chinese Films|date=22 August 2012|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHu returned to period drama in ''[[Xuan-Yuan Sword: Scar of Sky]]'', adapted from the [[Xuanyuan Sword|video game of the same name]], where he also acts as the series' producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2011-08-10/17383383142.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u8f69\u8f95\u5251\u4e4b\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5\u300b\u80e1\u6b4c\uff1a\u8fd9\u6b21\u89d2\u8272\u6709\u70b9\"\u6076\"|date=10 August 2011|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> His excellent portrayal of his character's paradoxical personality earned him another Best Actor in the fantasy genre at the 2012 Huading Awards,<ref name=huading>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u534e\u9f0e\u5956\u63ed\u6653 \u5f20\u5609\u8bd1\u674e\u5c0f\u7490\u5206\u83b7\u89c6\u5e1d\u540e|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2012-12-10/22263808330.shtml|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=10 December 2012|accessdate=11 December 2012|language=zh}}</ref> as well as the Most Popular Actor award at the 4th [[TV Drama Awards Made in China|China TV Drama Awards]].<ref name=anhui>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u5b89\u5fbd\u56fd\u5267\u76db\u5178\u843d\u5e55 \u5f20\u5609\u8bd1\u5b59\u4fea\u5206\u83b7\u89c6\u5e1d\u540e|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2013-01-01/00143824972.shtml|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=1 January 2013|accessdate=17 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref> The same year, he participated in [[Chinese Entertainment Shanghai Limited|CES]]'s nano-movie ''Refresh 3+7''. He wrote the script for one of the stories ''Lights from the City'', and starred in 4 out of the 10 stories.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u300a\u5237\u65b03+7\u300b\u5c06\u767b\u4e1c\u65b9\u536b\u89c6 \u80e1\u6b4c\u9996\u4efb\u7f16\u5267|url=http://ent.163.com/12/0817/01/892RVGT000032KMI.html|website=[[NetEase]]|date=17 August 2012|accessdate=17 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref>\n\n===2013: Forays into theater===\n2013 has often been referred to as Hu Ge's year of Theatre plays. He acted as ''Patient No.5'' in [[Stan Lai]]'s ''A Dream Like a Dream'', which served as the opening act at the 1st Wuzhen Theatre Festival. Hu's performance in ''A Dream Like A Dream'' especially surprised many [[Theatre criticism|theatre critics]], and garnered positive reviews all round.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/opinion/2013/04/03/256343.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u5982\u68a6\u4e4b\u68a6\u300b\uff1a\u7528\u4eba\u751f\u767e\u6001\u5236\u9020\u68a6\u5883|website=Beijing Newspaper|date=3 April 2013|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://cul.sohu.com/20130402/n371477390.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u5982\u68a6\u4e4b\u68a6\u300b\u660e\u661f\u6210\u60ca\u559c \u80e1\u6b4c\u674e\u5b87\u6625\u81ea\u7136\u6734\u5b9e|date=2 April 2013|accessdate= 3 April 2013|language=zh}}</ref> He won the Best Actor award at the 2nd Denny Awards for his performance.<ref name=denny>{{cite news|url=http://yule.sohu.com/20130820/n384525970.shtml|script-title=zh:\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c4a\u5317\u4eac\u4e39\u5c3c\u56fd\u9645\u821e\u53f0\u8868\u6f14\u827a\u672f\u5956\u83b7\u5956\u540d\u5355|website=[[Sohu]]|date=20 August 2013|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nHe then starred as Xu Zhuang Tu in ''Forever Yin Xueyan'', a play based on [[Pai Hsien-yung]]'s novel of the same title performed in the [[Shanghainese|Shanghai dialect]]. He won the Most Popular Actor award at the Shanghai Culture Center,<ref name=shanghai>{{cite news|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/j/2013-09-24/10324013776.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u6f14\u8bdd\u5267\u8fde\u8fde\u83b7\u5956 \u300a\u5c39\u96ea\u8273\u300b\u518d\u767b\u4e0a\u6d77|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=24 September 2013|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref> and the Most Popular Theater Actor of the Year at the BQ Magazine Popular Artists Ceremony.<ref name=theater>{{cite news|url=http://yule.sohu.com/20131109/n389857779.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u83b7\u620f\u5267\u7ea2\u4eba\u5956 \u81ea\u5632\"\u5c0f\u80cc\"\u8d70\u7ea2\u9760\u53cc\u811a|website=[[Sohu]]|date=9 November 2013|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132016: Career resurgence and critical acclaim===\nIn 2014, Hu Ge starred in modern drama ''Life Revelations'' alongside [[Yan Ni (actress)|Yan Ni]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.qq.com/a/20140525/003219.htm|script-title=zh:\u300a\u751f\u6d3b\u542f\u793a\u5f55\u300b\uff1a\u80e1\u6b4c\u628a\u8138\u6454\u5230\u5730\u4e0a\uff0c\u70ed\u4e86\u4eba\u5fc3|date=25 May 2014|website=Tencent|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> and won the People's Choice award at the 9th [[Seoul International Drama Awards]] for his performance.<ref name=seoul>{{cite news|url=http://english.sina.com/entertainment/2014/0905/734094.html|title=Hu Ge and Joseph Cheng win People's Choice award at SDA|website=[[Sina Corp|Sina English]]|date=5 September 2014|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> He then starred in historical romance drama ''[[Sound of the Desert]]'', based on the novel ''[[Ballad of the Desert]]'' written by [[Tong Hua (writer)|Tong Hua]]. Originally cast in the role of the leading male role, Hu decided to take on the role of the second male lead instead, as it was a type of character he has never played before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.163.com/14/1025/13/A9DGKI4800014AED.html|script-title=zh:\u4e3b\u52a8\u5f03\u6f14\u7535\u89c6\u5267\u300a\u98ce\u4e2d\u5947\u7f18\u300b\u7537\u4e00\u53f7\u2014\u2014- \u80e1\u6b4c\uff1a\u559c\u6b22\u65b0\u9c9c\u611f|date=15 October 2014|website=Netease|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> The same year, he garnered a Best Supporting Actor nomination at the 21st [[Shanghai Television Festival]] for his performance in acclaimed war drama, ''Forty Nine Days: Memorial''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.163.com/14/1215/06/ADG3IUEE00014AED.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u56db\u5341\u4e5d\u65e5\u796d\u300b\u70ed\u64ad\u80e1\u6b4c\u6f14\u7ece\"\u810f\u5e05\"\u786c\u6c49|date=15 December 2014|website=Netease|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=fiesta>{{cite news|url=http://yule.sohu.com/20150525/n413708635.shtml|script-title=zh:\u767d\u7389\u5170\u5956\u63d0\u540d\u63ed\u6653 \u80e1\u6b4c\u51ed\u501f\u300a\u56db\u5341\u4e5d\u65e5\u796d\u300b\u5165\u56f4|website=[[Sohu]]|date=25 May 2015|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> With three successful dramas, Hu won the Most Popular Actor award at the 6th China TV Drama Awards.<ref name=big>{{cite news|url=http://yule.sohu.com/20141218/n407070326.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u83b7\u6700\u53d7\u6b22\u8fce\u6f14\u5458 \u738b\u4e3d\u840d\u9881\u5956\u9080\u7ea6\u518d\u5408\u4f5c|website=[[Sohu]]|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Hu starred in espionage drama ''[[The Disguiser]]'', which was met with critical acclaim and dominated ratings.<ref>{{Cite web|title=War spy drama 'The Disguiser' dominates ratings|url = http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/942561.shtml|website=[[Global Times]]|date = 15 September 2015|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> This was followed by ''[[Nirvana in Fire]]'', a turning point in Hu's acting career,<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u63ed\u80e1\u6b4c\u5341\u5e74\u6f14\u7ece\u751f\u6daf\u6210\u540d\u8def\uff1a\u7531\u989c\u503c\u62c5\u5f53\u5230\u6f14\u6280\u6d3e\u7684\u8715\u53d8|url=http://ent.ifeng.com/a/20151015/42508343_3.shtml|website=ifeng|date=15 October 2015|accessdate=25 October 2015|language=zh}}</ref> and a commercial and critical success in its own right.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u300a\u7405\u740a\u699c\u300b\u53e3\u7891\u7206\u68da \u4e24\u5929\u7834\u4ebf\u64ad\u653e\u91cf\u5168\u7f51\u7b2c\u4e00|url=http://ent.people.com.cn/n/2015/0922/c1012-27620411.html|website=People's Daily|accessdate=25 October 2015|date=22 September 2015|language=zh}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' praised the story, acting and cinematography of the series, stating that it had restored viewers' confidence in Chinese period dramas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Winning success with sincerity: \u2018Nirvana in Fire\u2019 restores confidence in period shows|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/946888.shtml|website=[[Global Times]]|date=13 October 2015|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref> Hu then starred in modern drama ''[[Good Times (TV series)|Good Times]]'', written by ''Life Revelations'' writer Wang Liping.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ent.qq.com/a/20151016/019647.htm#p=1|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u9738\u5c4f\u6700\u540e\u4e00\u68d2 \u300a\u5927\u597d\u65f6\u5149\u300b\u4eca\u665a\u5f00\u64ad|website=[[Tencent]]|date=16 October 2015|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref> All three of his dramas in 2015 were listed under the \"2015 China TV Drama Selection\" by the [[State Administration of Press, Publication, Radio, Film and Television]].<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u5e7f\u7535\u300a2015\u4e2d\u56fd\u7535\u89c6\u5267\u9009\u96c6\u300b\u516c\u5e03 \u80e1\u6b4c\u4e09\u5267\u5165\u9009|url=http://ent.qq.com/a/20160217/040790.htm|website=[[Tencent]]|date=17 February 2016|accessdate=25 October 2015|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nHu Ge won awards at two of the most prestigious television awards in China for his role in ''Nirvana in Fire''. He won Best Actor at the 22nd [[Shanghai Television Festival]];<ref name=magnolia>{{cite news|url=http://www.china.org.cn/wap/2016-06/11/content_38643821.htm|title=Hu Ge, Sun Li win big at Shanghai TV Festival|website=China.org.cn|date=11 June 2016|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> and snagged a double victory by claiming both the Viewers' Choice award and the Most Popular Actor award at the 28th [[China TV Golden Eagle Award]].<ref name=eagle>{{cite news|url=http://english.cctv.com/2016/10/17/VIDE8XFuQAi7xccqf4QwhXPE161017.shtml|title=Actor Hu Ge becomes the biggest winner of TV drama evening|website=CCTV News|date=17 October 2016|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Hu starred in sports drama ''Go! Goal! Fighting!'' as a soccer coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2016-03-23/doc-ifxqnski7870863.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u65cb\u98ce\u5341\u4e00\u4eba\u300b\u66dd\u89d2\u8272\u6d77\u62a5 \u5b9a\u68634\u67081\u65e5|publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|date=23 March 2016|accessdate=16 February 2017|language=zh}}</ref> He returned to the big screen in December 2016, starring as an antagonist in the crime suspense film ''Cherry Returns''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/zz/2016-09-28/doc-ifxwevww1735109.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u90a3\u5e74\u590f\u5929\u4f60\u53bb\u4e86\u54ea\u91cc\u300b\u80e1\u6b4c\u53cb\u60c5\u51fa\u6f14|date=28 September 2016|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> The same year, ''CBN Weekly'' crowned him the most commercially valuable actor in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/beijing/2016-12/15/content_27708443.htm|title=Top 10 Chinese celebrities with most commercial value|work=[[China Daily]]|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: Hiatus and focus on films===\nHu announced that he will be departing temporarily from the film industry for the next two years, to seek further education at [[New York University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/celebrity/2015-12/07/content_22648082.htm|title=Hu Ge plans to take leave of absence from showbiz|work=China Daily|date=7 December 2015|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> The same year, Hu starred in ''[[Game of Hunting]]'', a drama produced by critically acclaimed director and screenwriter Jiang Wei. The series was filmed back in 2015 and premiered on [[Hunan TV]] in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2017-10-19/doc-ifymzqpq2303669.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u730e\u573a\u300b\u7ec8\u4e8e\u5b9a\u6863\uff01\"\u730e\u5934\"\u80e1\u6b4c11\u6708\u89c1|date=19 October 2017|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> Hu was later nominated for the Best Actor award at the [[Shanghai Television Festival]] for his role as a headhunter.<ref name=head />\n\nIn 2018, Hu was cast in [[Diao Yinan]]'s drama film ''[[The Wild Goose Lake]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mtime.com/2018/04/28/1580160.html|script-title=zh:\u5ed6\u51e1\u6842\u7eb6\u9541\u80e1\u6b4c\u4e07\u831c\u52a0\u76df\u5201\u4ea6\u7537\u7535\u5f71 \"\u767d\u65e5\u7130\u706b\"\u5bfc\u6f14\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u5357\u65b9\u8f66\u7ad9\u7684\u805a\u4f1a\u300b\u5f00\u673a|date=28 April 2018|website=Mtime|language=zh}}</ref> It was selected to compete for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/chinese-heartthrob-hu-goes-dark-side-cannes-debut-050326734.html|title=Chinese heartthrob Hu goes to dark side in Cannes debut|date=15 May 2019|website=AFP Relax News}}</ref> The same year, Hu made a [[guest appearances|guest appearance]] in romance film ''[[Last Letter]]'' directed by [[Shunji Iwai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/zz/2018-10-18/doc-ihmrasqr7024371.shtml|script-title=zh:\u5ca9\u4e95\u4fca\u4e8c\u7535\u5f71\u300a\u4f60\u597d\uff0c\u4e4b\u534e\u300b\u66dd\u89d2\u8272\u6d77\u62a5|date=18 October 2018|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Hu was cast as the male lead in the sports biographic film ''Li Na'' directed by [[Peter Chan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mtime.com/2019/03/26/1590348.html|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u9970\u6f14\u674e\u5a1c\u8001\u516c \u9648\u53ef\u8f9b\u65b0\u7247\u66dd\u5361\u53f8\uff01|date=26 March 2019|website=Mtime|language=zh}}</ref> The same year, he was cast in the adventure drama film  ''[[The Climbers (2019 film)|The Climbers]]'' .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mtime.com/2019/06/16/1594003.html|script-title=zh:\u9707\u64bc\uff01\u300a\u6500\u767b\u8005\u300b\u9996\u66dd\"\u70b9\u5c06\"\u7248\u9884\u544a \u5434\u4eac\u7ae0\u5b50\u6021\u5f20\u8bd1\u80e1\u6b4c \u7ec4\u6210\u56fd\u4ea7\u7247\"\u738b\u70b8\"\u9635\u5bb9|date=16 June 2019|website=Mtime|language=zh}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Accident and recovery===\nHu Ge was involved in a car accident on 29 August 2006 while traveling from [[Hengdian World Studios|Hengdian]] to Shanghai on the highway. He survived with severe injuries while his assistant died. Hu had to undergo surgery and the entire healing process took approximately one year. The filming of ''[[The Legend of the Condor Heroes (2008 TV series)|The Legend of the Condor Heroes]]'', which he was working on then, was temporarily halted due to his injury,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/s/m/2006-08-31/00501224311.html |script-title=zh:\u9047\u8f66\u7978\u80e1\u6b4c\u53ef\u80fd\u6bc1\u5bb9 \u7ecf\u7eaa\u79f0\u505a\u597d\u53bb\u56fd\u5916\u6574\u5bb9\u51c6\u5907 |date=31 August 2008|accessdate=31 August 2006 |publisher=[[Sina Corp]]|language=zh}}</ref> in addition to being unable to complete promoting his finished project ''[[The Young Warriors (TV series)|The Young Warriors]]'' with his fellow cast members. Hu Ge expresses how he felt of the incident through the performance of his single \"Dare to Love\", and filmed a music video with his co-star from the two series and friend [[Cecilia Liu]].\n\nSoon after the accident, he also published a book ''Scavenger of Happiness'', filled with his thoughts on the accident and post events, interesting childhood events, well wishes from good friends and previously unexposed pictures. This book documented in detail the process of how Hu Ge changed from a young idol with a smooth career path into an increasingly mature actor who could truthfully face life's problems as a scavenger of happiness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com/gb/2018-07-22/doc-iuiiszyy6920272.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\uff1a\u4e0d\u7ecf\u5386\u751f\u6b7b\uff0c\u600e\u4e48\u6f14\u7ece\u751f\u6b7b\uff1f|date=22 July 2018|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable \n|-\n!  Year\n! English title\n! Chinese title \n! Role \n! Notes\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[The National Anthem (film)|The National Anthem]]''||{{lang|zh-Hans|\u56fd\u6b4c}} || Student || Extra\n|-\n| 2002 || ''Pretend There's No Feeling''||{{lang|zh-Hans|\u5047\u88c5\u6ca1\u611f\u89c9}} || Kankan ||\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[The Ghost Inside (film)|The Ghost Inside]]''||{{lang|zh|\u7591\u795e\u7591\u9b3c}} || Shen Lang ||\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[The 601st Phone Call]]''||{{lang|zh-Hans|\u7b2c601\u4e2a\u7535\u8bdd}} || Xiaowen ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[The Butterfly Lovers (2008 film)|The Butterfly Lovers]]''||{{lang|zh-Hans|\u6b66\u4fa0\u6881\u795d}} || Ma Cheng'en ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[1911 (film)|1911]]''||{{lang|zh|\u8f9b\u4ea5\u9769\u547d}} || [[Lin Juemin]] ||\n|-\n| 2012 || ''Diva''||{{lang|zh-Hans|\u534e\u4e3d\u4e4b\u540e}} || Hu Ming ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2012-08-13/14563710200.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u5bb9\u7956\u513f\u6f14\u7ece\u300a\u534e\u4e3d\u4e4b\u540e\u300b\u8c08\u5a31\u4e50\u5708\u73b0\u5b9e|date=13 August 2012|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Just Another Margin]]''||{{lang|zh-Hans|\u5927\u8bdd\u5929\u4ed9}} || Black Emperor's Assassin || [[Cameo appearance|Cameo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/m/c/2014-01-20/22194084913.shtml|script-title=zh:\u80e1\u6b4c\u60ca\u559c\u52a0\u76df\u300a\u5927\u8bdd\u5929\u4ed9\u300b \u9020\u578b\u6d6e\u5938|date=20 January 2014|publisher=Sina Corp|language=zh|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> \n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Cherry Returns]]''||{{lang|zh-Hans|\u90a3\u5e74\u590f\u5929\u4f60\u53bb\u4e86\u54ea\u91cc}} || Yuan Ju || Special appearance\n|-\n|2018||''[[Last Letter]]''||{{lang|zh-Hans|\u4f60\u597d\uff0c\u4e4b\u534e}}||Zhang Chao||Special appearance\n|-\n|rowspan=2|20