.org/web/20180811105648/http://people.forbes.com/?profile%2Fdavid-r-goode%2F16431 |date=August 11, 2018 }} ''Forbes.'' Retrieved July 25, 2011.</ref> [[Northwest Airlines]] ([[Gary L. Wilson]]),<ref>\n[https://people.forbes.com/profile/gary-l-wilson/16504 Gary L. Wilson] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415192904/http://people.forbes.com/profile/gary-l-wilson/16504 |date=April 15, 2012 }} . ''Forbes.'' Retrieved July 25, 2011.\n</ref> [[Panda Restaurant Group]] ([[Tom Davin]]), [[PepsiCo]] ([[Karl von der Heyden]]),<ref>\n[https://people.forbes.com/profile/karl-m-von-der-heyden/27248 Karl M. von der Heyden.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210030545/http://people.forbes.com/profile/karl-m-von-der-heyden/27248 |date=February 10, 2012 }}  ''Forbes.'' Retrieved July 25, 2011.\n</ref> [[Procter & Gamble]] ([[David S. Taylor]]),<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=22783920&ticker=PG&previousCapId=764180&previousTitle=TRW%20Automotive%20Inc. David S. Taylor] \"Bloomberg.\" Retrieved August 16, 2015.</ref> [[Pfizer]] ([[Edmund T. Pratt, Jr.]]),<ref>\n[http://www.pfizer.com/about/history/edmund_pratt.jsp Pfizer Gallery of Leaders.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104084557/http://www.pfizer.com/about/history/edmund_pratt.jsp |date=January 4, 2009 }}  Pfizer. Retrieved July 25, 2011.\n</ref> [[The Bank of New York Mellon]] ([[Gerald Hassell]]),<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=170472&ticker=BK:US Gerald Hassell: Executive Profile and Compensation.] ''Bloomberg.'' Retrieved October 17, 2011.</ref> [[Wachovia]] ([[Robert K. Steel]]),<ref>[https://archive.today/20120722003347/http://topics.wsj.com/person/S/robert-k-steel/544 Robert Steel.]  ''The Wall Street Journal.'' Retrieved July 25, 2011.</ref> [[Volkswagen Group of America|Volkswagen]] ([[Jonathan Browning (UK businessman)|Jonathan Browning]]).\n\nCompanies founded by Duke alumni include the nation's wealthiest charitable foundation<ref>\n[http://philanthropy.com/free/articles/v16/i10/wealthiest.htm The Nation's 10 Wealthiest Foundations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091016215445/http://philanthropy.com/free/articles/v16/i10/wealthiest.htm |date=October 16, 2009 }}. ''[[The Chronicle of Philanthropy]]'', March 4, 2004. Retrieved January 12, 2011.\n</ref> at $31.9 billion:<ref>[http://www.gatesfoundation.org/about/Pages/foundation-fact-sheet.aspx Foundation Fact Sheet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531142915/http://www.gatesfoundation.org/about/Pages/foundation-fact-sheet.aspx |date=May 31, 2012 }}. ''[[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]].'' Retrieved July 4, 2011.</ref> [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]] ([[Melinda Gates]]),<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/businessweek/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=703941 Melinda Gates: Executive Profile and Biography.] ''Bloomberg.'' Retrieved July 25, 2011.</ref> [[The Carlyle Group]] ([[David Rubenstein]]), [[Boston Scientific]] ([[Peter Nicholas (businessman)|Peter Nicholas]]),<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/10/GU5A.html Peter Nicholas, The World's Richest People]. ''Forbes.'' Retrieved July 25, 2011.</ref> The Pritzker Group, principal owner of [[Hyatt Hotels Corporation|Hyatt Hotels]] and [[TransUnion]] ([[J. B. Pritzker]]), [[PIMCO]] ([[Bill H. Gross|William Gross]]), and [[1-800-Flowers]] ([[Granville Semmes]]).\n\nRecent notable startups founded by Duke alumni include [[Box (company)|Box]] ([[Dylan Smith (businessman)|Dylan Smith]]), [[Yext]] ([[Howard Lerman]]), [[Mint.com|Mint]] ([[Aaron Patzer]]), [[Coinbase]] (Fred Ehrsam), [[Plaid (company)|Plaid]] (Zach Perret), [[Duolingo]] ([[Luis von Ahn|Luis Von Ahn]]), [[Airtable]] (Howie Liu), and [[Neuralink]] (Max Hodak).\n\n=== Athletics ===\nManagement and ownership of professional athletic franchises include [[Adam Silver]] (NBA commissioner), [[John P. Angelos]]<ref>[http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1999-03-01/sports/9903010003_1_peter-angelos-foss-financial-officer Angelos' son moves up to No. 3]. ''The Baltimore Sun'', March 1, 1999. Retrieved July 29, 2011.</ref> (Executive Vice President of the Baltimore Orioles), [[Aubrey McClendon]]<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/profile/aubrey-mcclendon Aubrey McClendon] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729090315/http://www.forbes.com/profile/aubrey-mcclendon |date=July 29, 2011 }}. ''Forbes.'' Retrieved July 29, 2011.</ref> (former part owner of the Oklahoma City Thunder), [[John Canning, Jr.]]<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=74410 John Canning: Executive Profile and Biography]. ''Businessweek.'' Retrieved July 29, 2011.</ref> (co-owner of Milwaukee Brewers), [[Danny Ferry]]<ref>Mason, Stuart. [http://megasportsnews.com/?p=7685 Former Cavs general manager Danny Ferry to San Antonio]. ''Mega Sports News'', August 28, 2010. Retrieved July 29, 2011.</ref> (former general manager of the Cleveland Cavaliers), [[Stephen Pagliuca]]<ref>[http://www.nba.com/celtics/contact_stephen-pagliuca.html Stephen Pagliuca \u2013 Managing Partner & Alternate Governor]. ''NBA.com.'' Retrieved July 29, 2011.</ref> (co-owner of Boston Celtics), and [[Jeffrey Vinik]]<ref>[http://lightning.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=50500 Owners and Front Office \u2013 Tampa Bay Lightning]. ''NHL.com'' and ''Lightning Hockey LP.'' Retrieved July 29, 2011.</ref> (owner of the Tampa Bay Lightning).\n\nSeveral athletes have become stars at the professional level, especially in basketball's NBA. [[Art Heyman]], [[Shane Battier]], [[Corey Maggette]], [[Elton Brand]], [[Carlos Boozer]], [[Luol Deng]], [[Christian Laettner]], [[Bobby Hurley]], [[Grant Hill]], [[JJ Redick|J. J. Redick]], [[Grayson Allen]], [[Jabari Parker]], [[Jayson Tatum]], [[Brandon Ingram]], [[Jahlil Okafor]], [[Zion Williamson]] and NBA Champion [[Kyrie Irving]] are among the most famous.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/friv/colleges.cgi?college=duke NBA & ABA Players who Attended Duke University]. ''Sports Reference LLC.'' Retrieved July 29, 2011.</ref> Offensive linesman [[Lennie Friedman]] played for four [[National Football League]] teams, and [[Ed Newman]] was an All-Pro offensive lineman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/players/lenniefriedman/profile?id=FRI247193|title=Lennie Friedman|website=NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=220792&DB_OEM_ID=4200|title=Edward K. Newman|website=goduke.com}}</ref>\n\nMen's basketball coach [[Mike Krzyzewski]] led the US men's team to three [[gold medal]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=233997|title=Duke Olympians|publisher=|accessdate=February 13, 2018}}</ref> (2008, 2012, 2016), and [[Abigail Johnston]] won a [[silver medal]] in synchronized diving at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] while an undergraduate at Duke and competed in the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] while attending Duke Medical School.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/athletes-life/article/14376035/how-abby-johnston-manages-olympic-training-med-school|title=How Abby Johnston Manages Olympic Training \u2013 And Med School|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> [[Ibtihaj Muhammad]] was the first woman to compete at the [[Olympic Games]] while wearing a [[hijab]] and became the first female Muslim-American athlete to earn an Olympic medal at the 2016 Summer Olympics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/rio-2016-only-when-silence-falls-will-we-have-reached-that-blessed-acceptance-hijab-wearing-ibtihaj-a7179321.html|title=Muhammad out - but media won't let hijab-wearing American go quietly|date=August 8, 2016|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of colleges and universities in North Carolina]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Duke University}